    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">3, Gloucester Terrace, | Regent’s Park.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>3 May/73</date>
                    <salute>My dear Mr Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Many thanks for the name of the German book.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Now that I shall have another pair of shoulders on which to rest some of my burdens,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I should much like, if strength &amp; eyesight last, to escape sometimes to flowers— We shall see— At any rate I will get the book—</p>
<p>What a noble letter was that of Huxleys— I should like to have seen yours to him<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Sincerely yours | T H Farrer</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD had recommended <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3069.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hermann Müller’s</ref> <hi rend="italic">Die Befruchtung der Blumen</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5698.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">H. Müller 1873</ref>), on the fertilisation of flowers by means of insects (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8885.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Farrer, 28 April 1873</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Farrer probably refers to his marriage to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7859.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Katherine Euphemia Wedgwood</ref> on 30 May 1873 (see B. Wedgwood and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Wedgwood 1980</ref>, p. 303).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8872.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Huxley, 23 April 1873</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8873.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Huxley, 24 April 1873</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
